segments.text: One of the things I always noticed in a department when I was running it, anytime you're talking
about changes and suggestions from faculty, they pretend they're coming up with a big
original idea about how to do graduate program or how to do this, how to do that.
But when you investigate it in detail, you'll find that what they're proposing to do is
exactly the same way they did it where they came from.
And so I think anytime you get these outsiders coming in, you tend to, you do get some of
that mixture, but I'm not sure it's always that great.
Sometimes what we had was better than what they're trying to propose.
I'll tell you one other thing that I've noticed that I think A&M ought to improve on.
That is the way they treat their former presidents and so on.
Now, when I came here, Walton had been president, and I think he was the one that got us that
permanent fund, wasn't he?
Well, we began to get a better share.
I meant that was when he got, he was the one that looked up the law and got all that going.
And he was running the post office or something.
Then when Gilchrist stepped down, Fred Benson finally gave him an office over there in Zachary.
Then when Benson finally stepped down, old Flipsy wouldn't even give him an office anywhere for a long time.
And I just think that they lose a lot by not having these people more involved in.
Now, I went to this little junior college, this little Baptist junior college, and we had, I think we had chapel every morning.
And the guy that I took college algebra and trigonometry was born in about mid-1800s.
Dr. R.L.
Moore.
Big, tall, skinny guy, wore a frock-tail coat and wing-tip collars with a string tie.
And he didn't have any problem with what was right and wrong.
But he was very revered.
He sat up on the stage every day, and the president always deferred to him.
And he was still teaching a course in college algebra and trigonometry, and he taught one in Greek.
That was his, but he wanted to get associated with the average student.
Not just the preachers.
And every morning, I'll tell you this one, you might enjoy it.
Every morning in class, he would tell us a little moral story.
And it was also back in those depression days of encouraging students.
Now, I don't know whether we do enough of that.
Motivating them, just telling them, you've got to make something of yourself.
And he mentioned that Dick Wayne, that Hall that used to be in mathematics, was in one of his classes.
And he really worked hard.
And he went on to be professor at one of the greater universities, is what he said.
But he was, of course, against smoking and everything.
He was so against smoking that what he did, they said at one time, was buy up all of the tobacco in the little town there,
take it out on the middle of the campus, and burn it.
But anyhow, in those years, and that was about 1939, the number one hit parade song was,
I don't want to set the world on fire, I just want to start a flame in your heart.
And old Dr. Moore came in one morning, and he said, and he always called us young people.
He said, young people, I just don't know what this world's coming to.
He said, I was coming to walk, walking to work this morning, and I passed this young man.
He was pushing this wheelbarrow, and he was singing, I don't want to set the world on fire.
And young people, he was.
He wasn't.
He wasn't.
So, but I, now there is an example.
We're not getting, I think there's a tendency in all organizations to let us just bury the guy once we get through with him.
Instead of, if he was good enough to serve and run your organization, he would really be good enough to have around to help you.
And we need to, that's one of the things that we need to take advantage of.
I propose to.
I propose to President Bowen, and I couldn't think of a better title than alumni professor.
And I said, every year when the various faculty members retire, why not then try to look and say,
which of these would we like to be able to still claim were part of our team, still use their talents and abilities,
and ask the products of that department or that unit,
would you help us?
And I said, why not raise the money to give this person a small little honorarium
so that this person could still teach a course or do a little research.
We could call on for advice.
Randy Mattson, then executive director of the former students, he said, I could raise that money with a few phone calls.
But Dr. Bowen didn't see that as a good idea.
I wonder how he will feel when he retires.
Because see, just look what's happened to them.
Mm-hmm.
They're just walking around.
Nobody.
Yep.
Yep.
And Fred, old Flipsy, wouldn't even, and then Flipsy would just browbeat the hell out of you.
I'll give you one story that got him off of my back.
I was up there meeting with him and Skip Fletcher.
Boy, they just beat me all over the place about this and that, getting more money for this and more money for that, and a lot of things.
And so I just kind of let it slide off.
When I got back to the office, I decided the way I'll fix him is I'm going to write him a letter.
And I'm going to tell him, you told me several things this morning in our discussion.
And before I tell my faculty what you said, I want to make sure that I got the details correct.
Then I listed them.
I didn't hear anything from old Flipsy.
And then I throw him in.
He says, Charlie.
Charlie, we're going to make peace between your house and my house.
And he never did jump me anymore.
Now, he succeeded Dean Benson?
Well, no.
He was assistant to Richardson.
Oh, oh, oh.
And he and I got along fine after that, but he didn't try to come after me anymore.
He would intimidate people if he knew that he could.
You know, there's some people who run over others if they realize they can.
Yes.
And so that really cooled his heels.
And from then on, even Richardson would get him to go talk to me rather than do it himself
after I told him that if they wanted the job, they could have it.
But Richardson helped me a lot.
We worked together.
But I just, you know, stood my ground on that.
I didn't see any use of my stepping down at that particular time.
Trace, for this recording, after Fred Benson served as dean, who were the other deans?
Let's see.
Page was the next dean that was selected.
Describe him.
Well, he was a very nice individual.
Where'd he come from?
Let's see.
I can't remember.
It was a northern university.
He was in kind of an impossible situation.
Skip Fletcher had the tease.
If you have one man in charge of the Texas Engineering Experiment Station,
the other in charge of the academic, it'll never work
because I started out working under that one.
And Barlow and Mello had it.
And they didn't even talk to one another.
They sent letters up and down the hall on that new engineering building.
And each one of them expects you to work full-time for them,
is what the problem is.
And so Page had it all against him to begin with,
but he didn't really have any guts.
And he wouldn't go after, I don't think he went after money like he should have for us.
Because I... Our operating budgets were so small
that I used most all my gift and grant funds to do things
that I should have been spending state money on.
All travel.
I paid for it with gift and grant.
Go give papers.
I paid for that with gift and grant money.
And I couldn't get him to...
He wouldn't stand up for you over there.
And so that was...
I think he's a nice...
He's a nice individual, pleasant.
But he just didn't have the grit to stand up to somebody
to tell them, you know, we need this.
Who was next after him?
I guess they had several interims in there.
McDonald was an interim for a while.
And I guess that was about the next one.
And I guess the next one was Richardson.
Describe him, where he came from.
He came from MIT.
And I think he's...
He's a real good manager.
He doesn't like any confrontation at all.
He can hardly...
But he's really good at one-to-one discussions.
But he didn't like to have anybody criticize...
You know, a lot of times things really ought to be debated
even if people get a little hot
to find out what the real facts are.
Get them out and open.
And he didn't like this.
He didn't like...
He's just an individual.
It's a little...
He seems to be kind of timid.
He's not a good speaker.
He did all right running.
I think he did a good job,
except he was just a little timid on some of those things.
And he had Flipsy doing all of the nasty work.
He had him doing it for him.
But I think he was good,
and he was also good when he got into the higher position.
But he was not a good public representation
of Texas A&M University.
You need a man.
You need a man that can get up there and speak.
And he couldn't do it.
Describe to someone who might not be aware
of the realities of the College of Engineering,
Texas Engineering Experiment Station,
and the Texas Engineering Extension Service.
Explain how those are related
and describe their functions.
All right.
The Texas A&M...
The College of Engineering is a part of Texas A&M University.
The Texas Engineering Experiment Station
is a separate state agency on a chart.
It would occupy a position parallel to Texas A&M University.
And also, as I recall,
Texas Extension Service is the same way.
And I'm not sure whether TTI is.
It may be...
And where do they report?
They report...
They report now to the...
Well, they've had them report,
and they've had them report to different ones.
They report now to the Dean of Engineering,
because the dean is in charge of all of it.
One time, they reported to different people,
and there's where all the problems,
because the poor little old faculty member,
he has to work for both of them,
all three of them.
And so all the problems come down,
and he's the stretch.
And you, as a department head,
needed to be able...
I had to work with all of them.
Yeah.
And you...
You might want to get funding from all of them.
I'll tell you one other thing
that I think that universities don't work nearly hard enough at.
In fact, sometimes they go the wrong ways.
Well, there are two things.
One of them, just remind me if I don't come back to it,
is the coursework,
and another one is on funding people.
The one on funding.
All the time I was head of the department,
I was able to keep everybody on a 12-month basis,
regardless of whether they had research or not.
And we did that by using gift and grant funds,
and I just juggled it to where we made it work,
because it's very difficult to live on a nine-month salary.
And so I felt like everybody that's around the university
ought to be full-time employed.
And I think that one of the things that stirs up more resentment
on a university campus is having professors on a nine-month basis,
and administrators whom they are not really
over-enthusiastic about to begin with,
any administrator, on a 12-month basis.
And here these people are trying to get by on a nine-month basis.
And I think that what we ought to do is we've got a big plant,
millions of dollars invested in the facilities here.
We ought to expand the summer program
to where we've got 12-month employment throughout the year.
We're not an agricultural society.
anymore that was the reason that was originally set up we ought to get around to the fact that
we are a 12-month operation and that we need full-time employees and and i think you'd get
a lot more loyalty among employees if you had because these that can't get it and it's very
difficult in some areas to get research during the summer and this shouldn't be the way we operate
and we should try to do it on a 12-month basis and have people doing something there ought to be a
and i think there's a lot of students that want to take courses more course in the summer can't
get them because the money's not allocated for summer courses they're trying to seem to be trying
to keep those down but they ought to be going the other way just try to get more more summer courses
jumping way back now as in those 23 years that you were department head

And I did a lot of work on distillation.
In fact, I've got two papers.
I'm trying to get out of the field, but I've got two papers right now
that are going to be published.
And one of them is going into a journal where one of the editors are retiring
and they ask me to write a paper.
And I did, and I used a concept I've been using in teaching a class.
And I wrote it up, and sure enough, it's accepted.
It really wasn't any experimental research.
It was just a concept.
It was ability, technique for representation of indimensional space
in not just three, four, five, in two-dimensional space
and represent all the complexities there in two dimensions.
And it's real simple.
It's very similar to just representing it for two components.
And then another one that I've got coming out,
I didn't really think about getting a paper.
A guy from Vladivostok, a Russian, wrote me on email
that he'd like me to send him some of the papers that we had.
And instead of doing that, what I did was just sit down.
I said, well, that poor guy doesn't have any money,
can't even buy the papers and so on.
What I'll do is just sit down.
I'm going to derive him some equations
and give him ones that we haven't ever published before.
And so I did, and he's ended up,
he took those and made the problem a little bigger.
And he's got a paper written now.
I'm going to be a publisher with him.
From Vladivostok.
It's on the eastern front over there of Russia.
Who were the big,
were there any key industry supporters for chemical engineering?
Research here during your years?
Oh yeah, we had Dow continue to support us some.
And there weren't no real big ones, but enough grants.
Dow, I've got $20,000 a year to help me do this numerical stuff
and theoretical developments, which was a good,
back in those days, that's a good little sum of money

So we had some money like that.
We had a lot.
I also had some from National.

in to keep the research program going
and pay the graduate students as well.
Under your leadership, which do you think was more important?
The theoretical or the practical?
I don't know that there was all that much that really can't be divided that well down the line
because there's a lot of theoretical concepts involved in a lot of them
that can be practical problems.
And I don't know that I'd want to make a judgment on that.
Of these key faculty, in your years of leadership,

Did we lose some key faculty members to industry or another institution that?

The only one, we lost one or two, but we weren't concerned about it

We brought a whole group of young ones.
